    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4279270753" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4279270753" />
    <a title="Wick Welker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53069903-wick-welker"><img alt="Wick Welker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456500350p2/53069903.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4279270753?book_show_action=true">Oct 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Wick Welker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Wick Welker" href="/user/show/53069903-wick-welker">Wick Welker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53069903-wick-welker?shelf=economics">economics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53069903-wick-welker?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53069903-wick-welker?shelf=nonfiction-favorites">nonfiction-favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/53069903-wick-welker?shelf=politics">politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4279270753" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18026925616635144514"><b>Capital is king.</b><br/><br/>This terrible review will not do <i>Capital in the 21st Century</i> any justice at all. This macroeconomic book is incredibly scholarly and written from what appears to be an objective viewpoint. In retrospect, listening to this as an audiobook was a terrible idea. It’s not that the book is overly complex for a layman or inaccessible, it’s just that you really need to absorb the material through graphs and some minor algebra to follow a lot of lines of reasoning throughout the book. The</span>
  <span id="freeText18026925616635144514" style="display:none"><b>Capital is king.</b><br /><br />This terrible review will not do <i>Capital in the 21st Century</i> any justice at all. This macroeconomic book is incredibly scholarly and written from what appears to be an objective viewpoint. In retrospect, listening to this as an audiobook was a terrible idea. It’s not that the book is overly complex for a layman or inaccessible, it’s just that you really need to absorb the material through graphs and some minor algebra to follow a lot of lines of reasoning throughout the book. The first half I probably only absorbed ⅓ of the material. Things really picked up for me during the second half where we focused on wealth inequality and taxing. I LOVE this stuff.<br /><br />I’m just going to bulldoze past all the amazing data and analysis presented and get to what I care about: taxes. <b>Piketty clearly doesn’t believe that taxes are supposed to be used to finance the social state—they are used to limit wealth concentration and power</b>. The disparity with which how labor and capital are taxed is one of the direct reasons for this imbalance. Labor taxes are progressive, meaning they are tiered and increase progressively the higher the income a person makes. The incredibly high income taxes post-world war were a revolution in reigning wealth concentration and even reached as high as 90% at its peak. What people fail to understand is that insanely high tax rates were designed to only apply to the mega rich. No one else paid income taxes that were that high. And guess what… it worked. In addition to other reasons, the power of wealth was reigned in. <br /><br /><b>What’s been happening since the 1980s and into the 21st century, is a massive liberalization of capital, completely overtaking the issue of income disparity. The debate of how we should tax income is a gobsmacking political distraction from the real problem: capital is not taxed enough.</b> Who cares if the top income earners are taxed at 35 or 45%? It’s not going to do a damn thing when capital itself completely side steps substantial taxation. Corporate taxes, capital gains, dividends, estate wealth, inherited wealth and shareholder capital—none of it is taxed enough and it is exactly where all the wealth is today. <b>Labor taxes are punitive and pointless. Why punish employment by having a payroll tax? Why disproportionately tax the poor with a sales tax? Why punish people for having jobs?</b> We need a global wealth tax, an estate tax and inheritance tax and a corporate tax of something like 40%.<br /><br /><b>By taxing capital more, we will shrink the influence of money in all the other aspects of our societies particularly in politics, law making and monopolized markets.</b> Money is power and the capital holders of this world have plenty of both. The US government doesn’t even need the taxes to generate revenue because it's a fiat currency that can fund whatever it wants at any time. The entire point of taxes is to incentivize behavior and limit wealth concentration. Piketty went a lot into this stuff and I loved it.<br /><br />Anyway, I’ve only discussed about 0.1% of the book. I highly recommend this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18026925616635144514" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


